    "shortDesc": "Gastric ulcer, unsp as acute or chronic, w/o hemor or perf",
    "longDesc": "Gastric ulcer, unspecified as acute or chronic, without hemorrhage or perforation",
    "plainEnglish": "A gastric ulcer is a painful sore in the lining of your stomach, usually caused by bacteria (H. pylori), stress, or certain medications like aspirin. This code describes an ulcer that is present but has not caused bleeding (hemorrhage) or a hole (perforation) in the stomach wall, and doctors aren't sure if it's a new ulcer (acute) or a long-standing one (chronic). You might experience burning stomach pain, bloating, or nausea.",
    "whoUses": "Gastroenterologists, primary care physicians, and emergency medicine doctors use this code when diagnosing or documenting stomach ulcers. It commonly appears on patient EOB statements for hospital visits, endoscopies, or outpatient clinic visits related to upper abdominal pain or gastrointestinal symptoms.",
