    "code": "K76.0",
    "rawCode": "K760",
    "shortDesc": "Fatty (change of) liver, not elsewhere classified",
    "longDesc": "Fatty (change of) liver, not elsewhere classified",
    "plainEnglish": "Fatty liver means fat has accumulated in your liver cells, making the organ larger and less able to function properly. This can happen for various reasons, including obesity, diabetes, alcohol use, or metabolic problems, and often causes no symptoms—many people don't even know they have it until a scan or blood test reveals it. Over time, if left untreated, fatty liver can lead to inflammation and scarring of the liver tissue.",
    "whoUses": "Hepatologists, gastroenterologists, internists, and primary care physicians use this code during routine exams or when investigating abnormal liver function tests. It frequently appears on patient EOB statements when imaging studies (like ultrasound or CT) or liver function blood work are performed, as fatty liver is one of the most common liver conditions identified in clinical practice.",
