    "rawCode": "K921",
    "shortDesc": "Melena",
    "longDesc": "Melena",
    "plainEnglish": "Melena is the medical term for black, tarry stools that occur when there is bleeding in the upper parts of your digestive system (stomach, esophagus, or small intestine). The blood gets digested as it passes through your system, which is why it appears black rather than red. This can be caused by ulcers, severe acid reflux damage, bleeding vessels, or other conditions affecting the upper GI tract.",
    "whoUses": "Gastroenterologists, emergency medicine doctors, and primary care physicians use this code when patients present with upper gastrointestinal bleeding. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients who have had GI bleeding evaluations, endoscopies, or hospitalizations for gastrointestinal hemorrhage.",
